Fixes #585 ü¶ï

### What happened?

The current schema does not conform to the JSON-RPC 2.0 standard. In particular, the schema allows requests and responses without "jsonrpc" and "id" properties. The latter one is particularly important because it is the value that allows peers to correlate responses to the requests. For example, here's how `CancelTaskRequest` is currently defined:
```json
{
     ...
      "CancelTaskRequest": {
        "properties": {
          "jsonrpc": {
            "const": "2.0",
            "default": "2.0",
            "title": "Jsonrpc",
            "type": "string"
          },
          "id": {
            "anyOf": [
              {
                "type": "integer"
              },
              {
                "type": "string"
              }
            ],
            "title": "Id"
          },
          "method": {
            "const": "tasks/cancel",
            "default": "tasks/cancel",
            "title": "Method",
            "type": "string"
          },
          "params": {
            "$ref": "#/$defs/TaskIdParams"
          }
        },
        "required": [
          "method",
          "params"
        ],
        "title": "CancelTaskRequest",
        "type": "object"
      },
     ...
}
```
**It validates against requests that do not contain the "id" field.**

Also, the "jsonrpc" property should not have the default value present in the schema. I believe it is a consequence of schemas with fields defined as with `... = [default value or factory]` being generated from pydantic models, e.g.:
```python
class MyModel(BaseModel):
    field1: [type] = [default value or factory]
```

P.S. Also, see a [comment](https://github.com/google/A2A/pull/271#issuecomment-2825087251) that explains unnecessary "null" types that were also likely caused by the left-hand side of `field: str | None = None`. I know that the "null-types" issue was recently resolved; this is a different issue.

